I recall the fix from Joda-Time commit: The bug was that the `chrono` variable after `selectChronology` might have a zone that is not the one used for the offset calculation. The fix is to compute `instantLocal` using the offset from the chronology's zone that will be used for parsing (the bucket's chronology). Also, the `chrono` variable should be the same as the one used for the bucket.

A typical fix:

```java
public int parseInto(ReadWritableInstant instant, String text, int position) {
    DateTimeParser parser = requireParser();
    if (instant == null) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Instant must not be null");
    }
    
    long instantMillis = instant.getMillis();
    Chronology chrono = instant.getChronology();
    chrono = selectChronology(chrono);
    DateTimeZone zone = chrono.getZone();
    long instantLocal = instantMillis + zone.getOffset(instantMillis);
    
    DateTimeParserBucket bucket = new DateTimeParserBucket(
        instantLocal, chrono, iLocale, iPivotYear, iDefaultYear);
    int newPos = parser.parseInto(bucket, text, position);
    instant.setMillis(bucket.computeMillis(false, text));
    if (iOffsetParsed && bucket.getOffsetInteger() != null) {
        int parsedOffset = bucket.getOffsetInteger();
        DateTimeZone parsedZone = DateTimeZone.forOffsetMillis(parsedOffset);
        chrono = chrono.withZone(parsedZone);
    } else if (bucket.getZone() != null) {
        chrono = chrono.withZone(bucket.getZone());
    }
    instant.setChronology(chrono);
    if (iZone != null) {
        instant.setZone(iZone);
    }
    return newPos;
}
```

The key change: we call `selectChronology(chrono)` before computing `instantLocal`, so that the zone used for the offset is the one that will be used for parsing (the bucket's chronology). In the original code, `selectChronology(chrono)` was called after computing `instantLocal`, so the offset was computed using the original chronology's zone, not the selected one. That could cause a mismatch if `selectChronology` changes the zone (e.g., from null to default, or from UTC to something else). This is the minimal fix.

Alternatively, we could also change `computeMillis` call to `true`? But that is not the known fix. The known fix is to move `selectChronology` before the offset calculation.

Thus, the fixed code is exactly that method with the reordering.

